{
  "answer": "**No work in the corpus contains extensive philosophical analysis of the relation between learning (or knowledge) and authority akin to modern treatises on epistemology and power (e.g., no equivalents to Plato's *Republic* or Locke's writings on consent).** However, two works offer explicit reflections, primarily in religious-legal and political contexts:\n\n- **Manusmṛti** (by Manu): This text repeatedly reflects on how Vedic learning confers spiritual and social authority on Brahmins, superseding biological kinship, age, or wealth. It positions knowledge of the Veda as the basis for true superiority and \"greatness\" among Brahmins, while contrasting it with authority derived from valor (Kshatriyas) or wealth (Vaishyas). For instance, \"Not by years, not by gray hairs, not by wealth, not by kin did the sages make the law; he who is learned among us is the great one.\"[^1] The *ācārya* (Veda teacher) is \"more venerable\" than the biological father because Vedic birth is \"eternal,\" granting paternal-like authority.[^2]\n\n- **Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens** (by Johann Gottlieb Fichte): This pamphlet explicitly argues that free learning/thought (*Denkfreiheit*) is an inalienable human right foundational to personhood, morality, and liberty, which princes illegitimately claim authority to suppress for political control. Thought's freedom resists external authority, as \"no stranger may rule over him\"; suppressing it reduces humans to \"animals.\" Princes derive power from society but cannot alienate thought, the \"prerogative of humanity.\"[^3]\n\nOther works mention authority (e.g., various Smṛtis like Aṅgirasa or Bṛhaspati discuss legal/kingly authority) or learning (e.g., student vows in Manusmṛti), but lack explicit reflection linking the two concepts.[^4] Searches for phrases like \"learning authority,\" \"knowledge authority,\" or \"teacher authority\" yielded no results, and broader reviews confirmed the scarcity.\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 2*, [para p-7223f8](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-7223f8).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 2*, [para p-7c01c0](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-7c01c0).\n\n[^3]: Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens, *Chapter 2*, [para p-e62dae](/works/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-e62dae).\n\n[^4]: E.g., Aṅgirasa Smṛti, *Chapter 1*, [para p-f25d76](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-f25d76).",
